etymology:
First written record is apparently Kartarı 1986 where the dish is described as originating in Mersin between about 1978 and 1980 through a synthesis of local Turkmen culinary traditions and migrants from Southeastern Anatolia. At the time of writing (1986), Tantuni did not exist even in nearby cities like Tarsus (25 km away) or Adana. The origin of the word tantuni is uncertain. According to a vendor named Hasan Usta, interviewed in Kartarı 1986, the name was given when they started selling the meat sauté on mobile carts about 7–8 years prior to the article. Hasan Usta claims the word is Arabic and means "soft food".
Formally fits Armenian տանտուն (tantun, “a tandoor room in a traditional house”) used in the Van dialect, but it is not known to have referred to a food.
